Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button (in `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with back command and dirty tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Back()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard changes and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back button (in `AppShell.xaml.cs`)

The custom `BackButtonBehavior` only handles the **toolbar** back button. To also intercept the Android hardware back button or swipe-back gesture, add a navigation guard:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the toolbar button — it replaces default back behavior, so your command must call `GoToAsync("..")` itself.
- `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` catches system-level back (hardware button, swipe). The deferral is **required** because `DisplayAlert` is async.
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so you only intercept back navigation, not forward pushes.
